ight political parties in each country. It discusses parties individually, detailing their ideological features, strategy, internal organisation and leadership, and compares their political, social, economic, ethno-cultural and international characteristics. It reveals the main factors that were influential in the successes and failures of the far right, and offers a comparison between the typical far right voter living in the Balkans and his counterpart in Western Europe. The implementation and enforcement of legislature such as hate speech laws is also examined, along with other legal issues affecting the extremist parties in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical partieszBalkan Peninsula. 0aRight and left (Political science)zBalkan Peninsula. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aAlbania.  aBalkan.  aBulgaria.  aCroatia.  aFar right.  aMacedonia.  aMontenegro.  aRadical right.  aRomania.  aSerbia.1 aStojarová, Věra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611203340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526112033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526112033/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles